WEBVTT

00:01.000 --> 00:04.000  
<c.enthusiastic>Supernovae are full of mystery.</c>
We still don’t fully understand what makes them explode.

00:09.000 --> 00:12.000  
<c.happy>That’s partly because they’re impossible to predict.</c>  
We know what type of star is set to detonate, but have no way of knowing exactly when.

00:19.000 --> 00:22.000  
<c.angry>In fact, most of the data we have about these spectacular events comes from studying their remnants,</c>

00:22.000 --> 00:25.000  
in many cases hundreds, if not thousands of years after they began.

00:31.000 --> 00:35.000  
That or a stroke of dumb luck where we just happened to be looking in the right direction at the right time.

00:35.000 --> 00:39.000  
But earlier last year, this changed.

00:42.000 --> 00:47.000  
We finally captured a supernova as it was exploding…

00:47.000 --> 00:49.000  
and on purpose.

00:49.000 --> 00:56.000  
Finding it just hours after it began, this is one of the earliest detections we’ve ever made -

00:56.000 --> 00:59.000  
and it’s shown us something we’ve never seen before:

00:59.000 --> 01:01.000  
the shape of the explosion.

01:01.000 --> 01:05.000  
It might sound like an unusual thing to get excited about,

01:05.000 --> 01:10.000  
but this discovery has the power to unlock the inner workings of exploding stars

01:10.000 --> 01:13.000  
and answer centuries old conundrums.

01:13.000 --> 01:17.000  
What are the mysterious mechanisms that drive a supernova?

01:17.000 --> 01:23.000  
How does a core collapse inward then suddenly explode outward?

01:23.000 --> 01:26.000  
And why do some supernovae fail?

01:26.000 --> 01:32.000  
Thanks to new data from the ATLAS survey, we’re edging closer to answers.

01:32.000 --> 01:34.000  
I’m Alex McColgan and you’re watching Astrum.

01:34.000 --> 01:38.000  
Join me today as we watch a star explode in real time,

01:38.000 --> 01:40.000  
decode the shape of its blast,

01:40.000 --> 01:44.000  
and find out what really happens in those critical seconds

01:44.000 --> 01:49.000  
before a star rips itself apart.

01:49.000 --> 01:52.000  
On the night of the 10th of April, 2024,

01:52.000 --> 01:56.000  
the ATLAS survey was conducting a routine sweep of the cosmos.

01:56.000 --> 02:01.000  
It consists of four wide-field telescopes positioned around the globe -

02:01.000 --> 02:04.000  
in South Africa, Chile, and two in Hawaii.

02:04.000 --> 02:10.000  
Together, they systematically scan the entire night sky every 48 hours,

02:10.000 --> 02:14.000  
imaging each region four times in that window.

02:14.000 --> 02:19.000  
This rapid revisit time helps catch fast-moving events as they happen

02:19.000 --> 02:23.000  
and at 3:21am UTC on the 11th of April,

02:23.000 --> 02:24.000  
that’s exactly what happened.

02:24.000 --> 02:31.000  
ATLAS detected something unusual: a single spot in the sky, brightening dramatically

02:31.000 --> 02:37.000  
over the previous 5.8 hours. Immediately, this reading triggered the telescope's

02:37.000 --> 02:43.000  
automated alert system. The news of the unknown transient spread to the astronomical community

02:43.000 --> 02:48.000  
across the world, who quickly got to work deciphering what it could mean.

02:48.000 --> 02:55.000  
23.8 million light years away, in the spiral galaxy NGC 3621,

02:55.000 --> 03:03.000  
a star had just died. What ATLAS caught was a Type II supernova, right as it happened.

03:03.000 --> 03:09.000  
Yi Yang from Tsinghua University in Beijing and his colleagues

03:09.000 --> 03:13.000  
knew what this meant. It was their chance to see, for the first time,

03:13.000 --> 03:20.000  
the true shape of a supernova explosion in real-time. But they had no time to waste.

03:20.000 --> 03:25.000  
In addition to being impossible to predict, the initial breakout period of a supernova

03:25.000 --> 03:31.000  
explosion is incredibly short-lived. Once they go off, their original geometry remains

03:31.000 --> 03:38.000  
intact for just hours. After that, the ejected material crashes into surrounding gas and dust,

03:38.000 --> 03:43.000  
warping and obscuring the blast’s original shape. The pristine fingerprint of the core

03:43.000 --> 03:50.000  
collapse - the very thing needed to understand how massive stars die - would be gone forever.

03:50.000 --> 03:54.000  
So to get a true reading, the researchers had to act fast.

03:54.000 --> 03:58.000  
While most of the world slept, Yang and his team worked through the night,

03:58.000 --> 04:04.000  
drafting an emergency proposal to the European Southern Observatory. They urgently needed time

04:04.000 --> 04:10.000  
on one of the most powerful instruments on Earth - the Very Large Telescope in Chile. If they were

04:10.000 --> 04:17.000  
going to measure the shape of the explosion, they had to start gathering data right away.

04:17.000 --> 04:25.000  
Luckily, ESO immediately approved the request and the VLT swung toward galaxy NGC 3621. Yang

04:25.000 --> 04:32.000  
and his team waited, with their hearts in their throats and eyes locked on their screens. This

04:32.000 --> 04:38.000  
was the moment of truth. Had they taken too long? Would they get a pure reading back,

04:38.000 --> 04:43.000  
or a scrambled mess of inputs from an already-warped explosion?

04:43.000 --> 04:51.000  
By the slimmest of margins, they’d pulled it off. Precious data started streaming in, painting a

04:51.000 --> 04:58.000  
picture of true, undistorted supernova geometry. Yang and his team were witnessing the birth cry

04:58.000 --> 05:09.000  
of supernova 2024ggi, and learning, at last, how the Universe makes its most violent fireworks.

05:09.000 --> 05:15.000  
Supernovae come in two main types, but we’ll focus on Type II here,

05:15.000 --> 05:18.000  
the kind Yang and his team observed.

05:18.000 --> 05:22.000  
Through a mix of physical theories, astronomical observations, and computer

05:22.000 --> 05:29.000  
simulations, we’ve managed to build a pretty respectable model of how we think stars die.

05:29.000 --> 05:35.000  
Models are really important in science, helping us test hypotheses and granting new insights.

05:35.000 --> 05:39.000  
But having programmers skilled enough to develop those models

05:39.000 --> 05:42.000  
is just as important as having the scientists who work with them.

05:42.000 --> 05:49.000  
And thanks to Brilliant, the sponsor of today’s video,

05:49.000 --> 05:54.000  
those programming skills are readily available to anyone - including me.

05:54.000 --> 05:56.000  
