07:30.000 --> 07:35.000  
Stars spend their lives fusing lighter elements into heavier ones,

07:35.000 --> 07:43.000  
by combining nuclei into more tightly-bound configurations.

07:43.000 --> 07:49.000  
This fusion process releases excess energy, creating an outward pressure that pushes

07:49.000 --> 07:56.000  
back against the star’s own gravity. This keeps the star in a stable, spherical shape.

07:56.000 --> 08:03.000  
Over billions of years, the star’s core works its way up the periodic table - fusing hydrogen into

08:03.000 --> 08:10.000  
helium, helium into carbon, carbon into oxygen, neon, magnesium, silicon, and finally iron.

08:10.000 --> 08:15.000  
But this is where the chain stops. If you want to fuse iron into something heavier,

08:15.000 --> 08:20.000  
that reaction won’t release energy - it will require an energy input instead.

08:20.000 --> 08:29.000  
Iron-56 has the lowest mass per nucleon out of every possible nuclear configuration, so every

08:29.000 --> 08:34.000  
chain of nuclear reactions will ultimately turn every other type of nucleus into iron-56.

08:34.000 --> 08:39.000  
Eventually, the star’s entire core becomes iron. It’s a dead end.

08:39.000 --> 08:44.000  
With no more energy-releasing fusion reactions available, the star has run out of fuel.

08:44.000 --> 08:49.000  
It stops burning. The outward pressure that has been holding it up against its own gravity disappears.

08:49.000 --> 08:52.000  
Without that support, the core collapses on itself at breakneck speeds.

08:52.000 --> 08:58.000  
The outer part of the core can reach velocities of 70,000 km per second, that’s 23% the speed of light!

08:58.000 --> 09:00.000  
The collapse is so violent that it crushes protons and electrons in

09:00.000 --> 09:08.000  
the inner core into neutrons. It also releases a flood of neutrinos - nearly

09:08.000 --> 09:15.000  
massless particles that carry away enormous amounts of energy.

09:15.000 --> 09:21.000  
The collapsing material slams into the newly-formed neutron core and rebounds,

09:21.000 --> 09:25.000  
creating a shockwave that propagates outward at thousands of kilometres per second —

09:25.000 --> 09:29.000  
a process known as core bounce.

09:29.000 --> 09:35.000  
But the shockwave doesn't make it far.

09:35.000 --> 09:42.000  
Within milliseconds, it stalls roughly 100-200 kilometres from the center as it plows through the

09:42.000 --> 09:48.000  
dense outer iron core. The extreme temperatures and pressures tear apart the heavy iron nuclei back

09:48.000 --> 09:54.000  
into lighter elements like helium - a process that absorbs enormous amounts of energy from the shock.

09:54.000 --> 10:00.000  
This is the moment where one of two things can happen.

10:00.000 --> 10:07.000  
If the shock stays stalled for more than about a second,

10:07.000 --> 10:16.000  
the star will keep accreting mass until it collapses into a black hole. There’s no bang,

10:16.000 --> 10:24.000  
no brilliant burst. Everything slips into the void, a failed supernova.

10:24.000 --> 10:30.000  
The more common and mysterious alternative is that the shock doesn’t stall, it gets revived.

10:30.000 --> 10:36.000  
Something - neutrinos, jets, magnetic fields, or some combination we don't yet

10:36.000 --> 10:42.000  
understand - transfers enough energy to allow the shockwave to continue and turn the implosion into

10:42.000 --> 10:48.000  
an explosion. Exactly how this happens remains one of the biggest unsolved mysteries in astrophysics,

10:48.000 --> 10:53.000  
and is why events like SN2024ggi are so tantalising to the scientific community.

10:53.000 --> 11:01.000  
The shockwave travels up through thousands of kilometres of stellar

11:01.000 --> 11:10.000  
material. The journey takes several hours, until finally,

11:10.000 --> 11:15.000  
it breaks through the outermost layer of the dying star. This is the breakout phase.

11:15.000 --> 11:22.000  
As it emerges, the shockwave creates a brilliant flash of ultraviolet and optical light,

11:22.000 --> 11:26.000  
releasing huge amounts of energy and heating the star’s outer layers to tens of thousands

11:26.000 --> 11:32.000  
of degrees. It’s only at this point that the supernova becomes visible for the first

11:32.000 --> 11:38.000  
time - reaching peak brightness over the next week or two.

11:38.000 --> 11:44.000  
And the beginning of this rising brightness is exactly what ATLAS saw in the early morning hours of the 11th of April, 2024.

11:44.000 --> 11:50.000  
ATLAS catching SN2024ggi as early as it did was a triumph.

11:50.000 --> 11:56.000  
But detection was only the opening move.

11:56.000 --> 12:01.000  
The real work began after the alert went out - a race against the clock

12:01.000 --> 12:07.000  
to put the right instruments on target before the explosion’s original geometry vanished forever.

12:07.000 --> 12:12.000  
That urgency was exactly why Yang and his team had fought for time

12:12.000 --> 12:18.000  
on the VLT. They weren’t just trying to see the supernova — they were after a

12:18.000 --> 12:25.000  
very specific signature hidden in its light, something only one instrument could reveal.

12:25.000 --> 12:33.000  
Mounted on the VLT is an instrument called FORS2 - the only one of its

12:33.000 --> 12:39.000  
kind in the southern hemisphere. It measures spectropolarimetry - how

12:39.000 --> 12:44.000  
light is polarised across different wavelengths of the visible spectrum.

12:44.000 --> 12:50.000  
Normally, light waves vibrate in all directions perpendicular to their direction of travel.

12:50.000 --> 12:57.000  
This is unpolarised light. But polarised light has waves that only vibrate in one direction.

12:57.000 --> 13:03.000  
For example, when sunlight reflects off a flat surface like water or glass,

13:03.000 --> 13:09.000  
it becomes partially polarised. It’s also why when you put on polarised sunglasses,

13:09.000 --> 13:15.000  
this glare disappears. They’re designed to filter out that kind of polarised light.

13:15.000 --> 13:22.000  
In the context of SN2024ggi, Yang was interested in polarised light because of what it could

13:22.000 --> 13:28.000  
reveal about the shape of the explosion. A perfectly spherical explosion scatters

13:28.000 --> 13:34.000  
light equally in all directions, producing no polarisation at all.

13:34.000 --> 13:39.000  
An asymmetric explosion on the other hand - one that is symmetrical along one axis,

13:39.000 --> 13:43.000  
like a football or peanut-shaped explosion - would polarise light in a specific pattern.

13:43.000 --> 13:48.000  
FORS2 can help scientists decode this pattern. When light enters the instrument,

13:48.000 --> 13:55.000  
it first passes through a rotating crystal plate that can shift the orientation of polarised light

13:55.000 --> 14:01.000  
by a precise amount. By moving this plate to different angles, the instrument effectively

14:01.000 --> 14:09.000  
rotates any polarised light, allowing it to measure polarisation in all directions.

14:09.000 --> 14:14.000  
Next, the light hits a Wollaston prism - a unique optical component which physically

14:14.000 --> 14:19.000  
separates the incoming beam of light based on the polarisation direction.

14:19.000 --> 14:24.000  
Light waves vibrating in one plane go one way, waves vibrating perpendicular to that go the other way.

14:24.000 --> 14:30.000  
Each beam is then split into its component colours,

14:30.000 --> 14:36.000  
creating two side-by-side spectra on the detector - one for each polarisation

14:36.000 --> 14:42.000  
orientation. By comparing how bright each wavelength is across the two spectra,

14:42.000 --> 14:48.000  
astronomers can determine how strongly the light is polarised and in which direction.

14:48.000 --> 14:56.000  
Knowing how the light from SN2024ggi is polarised tells us the shape of its explosion. From there,

14:56.000 --> 15:05.000  
we can predict the mechanism that caused it.

15:05.000 --> 15:14.000  
For over 50 years, scientists have tried to explain the physical processes that

15:14.000 --> 15:24.000  
revive a stalled shockwave and trigger a supernova explosion.

15:24.000 --> 15:31.000  
From the creative rubble emerged two leading ideas. The first says that neutrinos must have

15:31.000 --> 15:36.000  
something to do with it. We know the core collapse sends huge amounts of neutrinos

15:36.000 --> 15:40.000  
shooting into space. But in the incredibly dense region just above the neutron star,

15:40.000 --> 15:47.000  
even neutrinos have trouble getting through. It’s thought a tiny fraction of them deposit

15:47.000 --> 15:53.000  
their energy into the material above the core, heating it from below.

15:53.000 --> 15:59.000  
This creates a violent convection. If enough energy accumulates,

15:59.000 --> 16:05.000  
the shock surges back to life, and the star literally blows its top, exploding furiously.

16:05.000 --> 16:09.000  
But here’s the thing - the convection doesn’t heat the neutrinos evenly.

16:09.000 --> 16:15.000  
State-of-the-art 3D simulations led by Bernhard Müller at Monash University,

16:15.000 --> 16:21.000  
show these explosions are highly asymmetric. And we’ve observed real supernovae that fit

16:21.000 --> 16:26.000  
this model well - the Cassiopeia A supernova remnant, for example,

16:26.000 --> 16:35.000  
shows an asymmetric distribution of radioactive chemical elements like titanium-44 and nickel-56,

16:35.000 --> 16:41.000  
which trace back to asymmetries present from the onset of the explosion.

16:41.000 --> 16:46.000  
The second theory says jets are behind the boom instead. The collapsing core

16:46.000 --> 16:52.000  
forms a rapidly rotating neutron star surrounded by a disk of infalling material.

16:52.000 --> 16:57.000  
Magnetic fields threading through this disk get wound up and amplified by the rotation - twisted

16:57.000 --> 17:00.000  
tighter and tighter like a rubber band. These amplified magnetic fields channel material

17:00.000 --> 17:05.000  
into two powerful jets shooting out along the star's rotation axis, like cosmic blowtorches.

17:05.000 --> 17:13.000  
They punch through the star's envelope with tremendous force,

17:13.000 --> 17:22.000  
driving a fundamentally different explosion. In this scenario, the blast would produce

17:22.000 --> 17:27.000  
axial symmetry along the star’s spin. The explosion then expands along this axis,

17:27.000 --> 17:32.000  
leading to a football-shaped or olive-shaped geometry. We’ve seen this kind of structure

17:32.000 --> 17:42.000  
in other supernovae, like SN 2023ixf, whose explosion was also organised and elongated.

17:42.000 --> 17:46.000  
So, what do you think Yang’s VLT observations show for SN2024ggi?

17:46.000 --> 17:52.000  
Pause the video and comment below: an explosion if you think it is highly irregular

17:52.000 --> 17:57.000  
and asymmetric like the neutrino–driven model predicts, or an American football

17:57.000 --> 18:00.000  
if you think it is symmetrical along an axis like the jet model predicts.

18:00.000 --> 18:05.000  
So, moment of truth.

18:05.000 --> 18:10.000  
This is what SN 2024ggi looked like.

18:10.000 --> 18:18.000  
The spectro-polarimetry data collected by the VLT’s FORS2 revealed a clear, well-defined axis

18:18.000 --> 18:27.000  
of symmetry and an olive- (or football-) shaped explosion - technically a prolate ellipsoid.

18:27.000 --> 18:32.000  
At first, it seemed like a clear win for the jet-driven theory. If the

18:32.000 --> 18:39.000  
explosion were driven by neutrinos, it would’ve been completely asymmetrical.

18:39.000 --> 18:45.000  
Finally, we had the conclusive, observational data we’d always been missing. Case closed, right?

18:45.000 --> 18:52.000  
If only it were that simple.

18:52.000 --> 18:57.000  
These models are based on simulations, theoretical physics, and extrapolated

18:57.000 --> 19:06.000  
information from supernovae we caught much later, after the critical breakout phase window shut.

19:06.000 --> 19:12.000  
The neutrino-based model certainly has its shortcomings. A 2015 article from

19:12.000 --> 19:19.000  
the Royal Astronomical Society showed that 3D neutrino-driven simulations produce explosions

19:19.000 --> 19:26.000  
an entire order of magnitude less than what we’ve seen observationally, even in the most favourable

19:26.000 --> 19:32.000  
conditions. This suggests neutrino heating alone simply isn’t enough to explain the blast.

19:32.000 --> 19:38.000  
But the jet-driven theories aren’t flawless either.

19:38.000 --> 19:42.000  
2D models seemingly work well, but when astrophysicists simulate jet-driven

19:42.000 --> 19:48.000  
explosions in 3D, something strange happens. A team at Caltech introduced

19:48.000 --> 19:52.000  
a 1% wobble around the axis of symmetry of a rapidly rotating, magnetised stellar core.

19:52.000 --> 19:58.000  
That tiny change made the jets unstable. They twisted and kinked, winding around

19:58.000 --> 20:04.000  
the rotation axis like water streaming out from a garden hose left lying on the ground.

20:04.000 --> 20:07.000  
Instead of punching cleanly through the star and driving an explosion, the jets

20:07.000 --> 20:16.000  
produced two misshapen lobes of twisted, highly magnetised material that slowly pushed outward.

20:16.000 --> 20:25.000  
The explosion never happened - there simply wasn’t enough energy to trigger an explosion.

20:25.000 --> 20:31.000  
Yet SN2024ggi clearly exploded. So there must be something else going

20:31.000 --> 20:38.000  
on. Either our models are incomplete, or we’ve missed something else entirely.

20:38.000 --> 20:44.000  
The solution might lie in flipping the old theory on its head. What if the

20:44.000 --> 20:49.000  
fatal wobbling and kinking is actually an essential part of the explosion?

20:49.000 --> 20:55.000  
If jets rapidly jitter rather than maintain a stable axis,

20:55.000 --> 21:02.000  
they can't drill a clean channel through the star like in the classic jet-driven model. Instead,

21:02.000 --> 21:09.000  
they're forced to deposit their energy closer to the core, roughly a thousand kilometres

21:09.000 --> 21:13.000  
from the centre, through shock waves. These shock waves create hot, pressurised bubbles

21:13.000 --> 21:19.000  
that merge and expand, pushing the stellar material outward and driving the explosion.

21:19.000 --> 21:23.000  
The jets themselves are chaotic and unstable,

21:23.000 --> 21:26.000  
but the overall explosion geometry remains axially symmetric - just like SN 2024ggi.

21:26.000 --> 21:33.000  
So, where does this leave us?

21:33.000 --> 21:38.000  
Well, SN2024ggi definitively showed us that explosions can have organised

21:38.000 --> 21:44.000  
axial symmetry. And how it arises - whether through narrow jittering jets,

21:44.000 --> 21:49.000  
a magneto-rotational mechanism, or something else - remains a mystery.

21:49.000 --> 21:55.000  
We’re still unsure what role neutrinos play in explosions like this, if any.

21:55.000 --> 22:01.000  
It also raises questions about alternative mechanisms that could cause asymmetrical

22:01.000 --> 22:07.000  
supernovae like Cassiopeia A and others, which don’t follow axial symmetry. Are they in fact

22:07.000 --> 22:12.000  
caused by neutrinos, or something else? Which factors determine what kind of explosion occurs?

22:12.000 --> 22:20.000  
This might come as a shock, but we can’t know without more data. SN2024ggi is the

22:20.000 --> 22:25.000  
only breakout phase we’ve observed in such detail and measured in real

22:25.000 --> 22:32.000  
time. If we could somehow know when and where supernovae were going to explode,

22:32.000 --> 22:35.000  
we could make a point to track them all and look for the patterns.

22:35.000 --> 22:41.000  
And that’s exactly what researchers plan to do,

22:41.000 --> 22:47.000  
thanks to new full-sky surveys like ATLAS becoming increasingly popular. 2025 alone

22:47.000 --> 22:54.000  
saw the inauguration of the Vera C. Rubin Observatory Legacy Survey of Space and Time,

22:54.000 --> 23:01.000  
NASA's SPHEREx, and the latest data release of the Sloan Digital Sky Survey.

23:01.000 --> 23:08.000  
Astronomers are optimistic that with these new tools, they’ll be able to

23:08.000 --> 23:12.000  
regularly catch supernovae within 24 hours of explosion. If they notice an object is

23:12.000 --> 23:16.000  
absent from the previous night’s images, but then appears within a galaxy, they follow-up

23:16.000 --> 23:20.000  
immediately with spectroscopy to determine the object’s characteristics as fast as possible.

23:20.000 --> 23:22.000  
As more automated survey systems come online worldwide, our ability to catch transient events

23:22.000 --> 23:27.000  
in their earliest moments will only continue to improve. SN 2024ggi showed us our models

23:27.000 --> 23:30.000  
aren’t quite there yet. The next generation of observations should help us find the missing

23:30.000 --> 23:36.000  
piece, and solidify our understanding of how stars all over the Universe draw their final breath.

23:36.000 --> 23:41.000  
And I mean, who wouldn’t want to see more

23:41.000 --> 23:46.000  
supernovae getting caught in their explosive moments?

23:46.000 --> 23:51.000  
Thanks for watching!

23:51.000 --> 23:54.000  
